                     </persName>
                  , from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>JOHN LAZARUS GRAY. I am a <rs id="t18340703-212-viclabel1179" type="occupation">cheesemonger</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340703-212-victim1269 t18340703-212-viclabel1179"></join>. I was at the licensed victuallers' dinner, at the <placeName id="t18340703-212-crimeloc1180">Mermaid, at Hackney</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18340703-212-crimeloc1180" type="placeName" value="Mermaid, at Hackney"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18340703-212-crimeloc1180" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340703-212-off1177 t18340703-212-crimeloc1180"></join>, on the 26th of June - I went into the garden, and fell asleep - it was then one o'clock in the morning of the 27th- I was tired, but not in liquor - I suppose I slept three-quarters of an hour - when I awoke, the officer came to me and asked if I had lost any thing - I said, "No;" but I felt, and missed my two seals, ring, ribbon, and key, and my handkerchief - when I felt myself rather sleepy, I put my handkerchief in my trowsers pocket, and kept my hand on it - I had not noticed the prisoners there - I saw them searched - I cannot say whose pocket the ribbon and seals came out of; but the handkerchief came out of Jarvis's pocket.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BODKIN. Q. What time did you dine? A. It might be six o'clock; but I do not know exactly - I eat but very little, and very likely what I drank took the greater effect on me - I put my handkerchief in my pocket, not by the side - my watch did not come out - I could not get it out, the ring broke.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340703-212-person1270">
                  JOHN 
                  BEDFORD
               <interp inst="t18340703-212-person1270" type="surname" value="BEDFORD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340703-212-person1270" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340703-212-person1270" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an inspector of police. I was on duty - I saw the prosecutor asleep, and Mason was calling him to awake - I placed myself in a situation where I could see what transpired - I saw the seals hanging from the prosecutor's watch fob - I soon after saw Mason leave the prosecutor, and go some distance between the tables and join Jarvis, who was sitting alone smoking his pipe - Mason then went again and sat by the prosecutor - he did so a second time - he then went to him a third time - I then went up and collared him and Jarvis - I took them to the prosecutor, and awoke him up - his seals were gone then - I asked him if he had lost any thing - he said, "No," but he felt, and missed his seals and ribbon - I took the prisoners to the station-house, and in Jarvis's right hand pocket I found the ribbon and seals; and in his small-clothes I found the handkerchief - I went in the morning to the gardens, and under the seat I found the swivel of the watch - there was nothing found on Mason - Jarvis was sitting the length of this Court from the prosecutor - I saw Mason join him three times, and leave him.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Were there other persons in the gardens? A. Yes, smoking their pipes; but not at that place - a person sitting where Janvis was, could see the prosecutor - it was in a straight line, and no one was between them - Jarvis did not attempt to interfere at all - Jarvis said he had been drawn into it.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Mason's Defence. I never saw my fellow-prisoner till he was taken.</p>
               <p>(Mr. Jackson, of the Peacock, Trinity-lane, in whose employ Mason was, gave him a good character.)</p>
               <p>MASON - <rs id="t18340703-212-verdict1181" type="verdictDescription">
